10:59.409 --> 11:00.493
♪ <i>I get knocked down</i> ♪

11:00.577 --> 11:01.870
♪ <i>But I get up again</i> ♪

11:01.953 --> 11:04.247
♪ <i>You're never gonna</i>
<i>keep me down</i> ♪

11:04.330 --> 11:06.082
♪ <i>Do your ears hang low?</i> ♪

11:06.166 --> 11:08.835
-♪ <i>Do they wobble to and fro?</i> ♪
-(quiet chatter)

11:08.918 --> 11:10.211
-♪ <i>Can you tie them in a knot?</i>
-(laughter)

11:10.295 --> 11:12.464
♪ <i>Can you tie them in a bow?</i> ♪

11:12.547 --> 11:15.425
Oh, see, you like it. Yeah.

11:15.508 --> 11:17.927
It's a great gift, guys.
Thank you very much.

11:18.011 --> 11:20.347
That song certainly isn't gonna
ruin my life at all, is it?

11:20.430 --> 11:21.931
(laughs)

11:22.015 --> 11:24.601
Oh, my God,
I love his witty humor.

11:24.684 --> 11:26.019
-(chuckles)
-Oh.

11:26.102 --> 11:28.480
I'm gonna go get a drink.

11:30.815 --> 11:33.777
I mean, her bar's a little low
when it comes to "wit."

11:33.860 --> 11:36.029
But she's, you know,
she's the new Trojan girl,

11:36.112 --> 11:38.281
so if you ever
need any free condoms...

11:45.330 --> 11:47.540
Hey, Kate, how's the,
uh, how's work going?

11:47.624 --> 11:49.876
Yeah, great.
Last week was '90s week

11:49.959 --> 11:53.463
so, uh, the whole class
sang "Backstreet's Back."

11:53.546 --> 11:55.382
Pretty much my dream job.

11:55.465 --> 11:59.177
Now if it just paid something,
we'd really come out on top.

12:02.847 --> 12:04.557
Wow, Toby.

12:05.600 --> 12:07.686
It was a jab at the school,
not at you.

12:08.728 --> 12:11.481
Yeah. I'm gonna go put
the candles on the cake.

12:12.691 --> 12:15.318
♪ ♪

12:26.579 --> 12:28.206
(floor creaks)

12:36.172 --> 12:37.841
Hey.

12:40.927 --> 12:42.345
(crying softly)

12:52.522 --> 12:54.649
How do I know...

12:56.735 --> 12:59.696
How do I know when it's time
to end a marriage?

13:07.120 --> 13:08.788
I think you'll know.

13:08.872 --> 13:10.790
(sighs)

13:10.874 --> 13:14.127
If that time comes,
I think you'll know.

13:17.213 --> 13:21.134
If it comes to that,
<i>if</i> it comes to that...

13:23.053 --> 13:26.806
...you and the kids
will be fine. Okay?

13:29.225 --> 13:31.770
Look at me and Madison,
we managed to work things out.

13:31.853 --> 13:34.272
And I'm not saying
that's you and Toby.

13:36.399 --> 13:40.278
But if it is, you...
you will all be happy again.

13:44.616 --> 13:47.619
Hello? Do you have any eights?

13:47.702 --> 13:49.954
Huh? Oh, um, sorry, Jack.

13:50.038 --> 13:52.290
Um, no, go fish.

13:52.374 --> 13:53.792
KATE:
Philip?

13:53.875 --> 13:56.002
-Jack? It's dinnertime.
-(exhales)

13:57.045 --> 14:00.256
Don't worry. It's gonna go good.

14:00.340 --> 14:01.966
(exhales)
Thanks, pal.

14:02.050 --> 14:03.718
(laughing):
Spinach?

14:03.802 --> 14:05.261
Listen, I don't think
it's weird at all.

14:05.345 --> 14:07.055
Of course it is.

14:07.138 --> 14:09.140
You've got the entire
kindergarten chorus

14:09.224 --> 14:10.517
singing "Maneater."

14:10.600 --> 14:12.769
Whatever, they love it!

14:12.852 --> 14:14.896
Hey, listen,
you have my support.

14:14.979 --> 14:16.523
All right?
Whatever filth you decide

14:16.606 --> 14:17.982
to make those children sing,

14:18.066 --> 14:20.819
I will be at that piano,
accompanying you with bells on.

14:20.902 --> 14:24.656
Well, thank you, that is
what I like to hear.

14:24.739 --> 14:25.740
All right.

14:27.158 --> 14:29.202
Okay.

14:29.285 --> 14:30.829
(dishes clatter)

14:32.372 --> 14:34.624
Do you think you want
some desser...

14:35.625 --> 14:38.670
I'd accompany you anywhere
actually.

14:38.753 --> 14:41.965
Uh, I-I've known it
since our first date.

14:42.048 --> 14:43.800
You remember when
that mariachi band,

14:43.883 --> 14:45.427
they arrived at our table,

14:45.510 --> 14:49.556
and you took my hand,
and the rest is history.

14:49.639 --> 14:53.685
God, I love you, Kate.

14:53.768 --> 14:58.189
I love your germy, loud,
unrefined children.

14:58.273 --> 15:01.067
(laughing)

15:01.151 --> 15:03.111
My time with you has just--

15:03.194 --> 15:06.031
it's just been the happiest
time of my life.

15:06.114 --> 15:11.202
So, um, what do you say
we-we make it official?

15:11.286 --> 15:13.705
Will you... Will you marry me?

15:15.373 --> 15:18.668
Oh, before you answer...
Okay, now. Now.

15:20.211 --> 15:21.546
(laughter)

15:21.629 --> 15:23.006
Hailey, go, Hailey!

15:24.132 --> 15:26.343
(laughs)

15:26.426 --> 15:28.386
Yes. Yes, I will marry you.

15:28.470 --> 15:29.679
Yeah!

15:29.763 --> 15:31.765
♪ ♪

15:36.603 --> 15:39.022
We've been seeing you
for 16 months.

15:39.105 --> 15:42.359
How much longer are we supposed
to keep coming here?

15:42.442 --> 15:44.194
Until we fix our marriage.

15:47.322 --> 15:50.658
When's the last time you two
had dinner together?

15:50.742 --> 15:52.619
Just the two of you?

15:53.912 --> 15:56.247
♪ ♪

15:59.125 --> 16:02.671
-(Hailey crying)
-TOBY: Sweetie, sweetie,
just-just relax.

16:02.754 --> 16:05.298
Come on, Hailey.

16:05.382 --> 16:06.800
(crying continues)

16:06.883 --> 16:08.468
TOBY:
Hailey, Hailey, Hailey.

16:08.551 --> 16:11.221
Hailey, come on, come on. Shh.

16:15.058 --> 16:18.436
You look so nice.
I've always loved that dress.

16:18.520 --> 16:21.439
-Yeah, I know.
-(chuckles)

16:21.523 --> 16:22.649
Wow.

16:22.732 --> 16:24.651
Toby, dinner looks so good.

16:24.734 --> 16:26.152
Just trying
to make Dianne proud.

16:26.236 --> 16:28.905
Well, do you <i>feel</i> proud, Toby?

16:28.988 --> 16:30.365
What matters is how you feel.

16:30.448 --> 16:32.867
And, Kate,
how do Toby's feelings

16:32.951 --> 16:35.495
about his feelings
make you feel?

16:35.578 --> 16:38.206
(laughing)

16:41.001 --> 16:42.377
How was work today?

16:42.460 --> 16:45.130
Ah. Fine.

16:45.213 --> 16:48.925
I got out of there at 5:00
on the dot, so that's a bonus.

16:50.635 --> 16:52.554
Sorry.

16:55.223 --> 16:56.683
How was your day?

16:58.184 --> 17:00.437
-The usual.
-Mm.

17:07.569 --> 17:11.406
Mm. How was bedtime?
I heard a little drama.

17:11.489 --> 17:14.617
Yeah, Hailey was up in arms
that we couldn't do

17:14.701 --> 17:17.037
a sixth reading of <i>Corduroy.</i>

17:17.120 --> 17:19.748
Well, did you, uh, read
<i>Hush Little Polar Bear</i> last?

17:19.831 --> 17:22.167
'Cause it really winds her down.
You know.

17:23.251 --> 17:26.463
Uh, no. No, like I just said,

17:26.546 --> 17:29.966
she-she kind of had
a one-track mind for, uh,

17:30.050 --> 17:31.176
for <i>Corduroy</i> tonight.

17:31.259 --> 17:32.802
Okay.

17:36.431 --> 17:39.934
(scoffs) You know I put her
to bed all the time, right?

17:41.144 --> 17:42.479
No, you don't.

17:43.980 --> 17:45.440
Jesus.

17:45.523 --> 17:47.442
What? I mean, it's true.

17:47.525 --> 17:49.152
Like, you don't put her down
all the time.

17:49.235 --> 17:51.821
Okay. Here we go.

17:51.905 --> 17:54.074
Here we go what?
I heard her crying.

17:54.157 --> 17:56.493
And when I hear my daughter,
who never cries at bedtime,

17:56.576 --> 17:58.203
-crying at bedtime...
-Mm-hmm?

17:58.286 --> 18:00.080
I can't ask you about it to,
like, protect your ego?

18:00.163 --> 18:02.832
-I mean, just, I'm try...
-Yeah, maybe, for once,

18:02.916 --> 18:05.126
you could resist the urge
to criticize me.

18:05.210 --> 18:06.670
It wasn't a criticism...

18:06.753 --> 18:08.546
It certainly was a criticism.

18:08.630 --> 18:10.715
Okay, fine,
you put the kids to bed

18:10.799 --> 18:13.468
more often and they like it
better when you do it.

18:13.551 --> 18:16.054
Who cares? I do other things.
Like when they're sick,

18:16.137 --> 18:18.348
I use that little
snot grabber thing

18:18.431 --> 18:20.100
because it makes you gag.

18:20.183 --> 18:23.144
But do I make you feel guilty
about it? No. I just do it.

18:23.228 --> 18:24.187
Okay, well, congrats.

18:24.270 --> 18:25.814
You occasionally
clear their noses.

18:25.897 --> 18:28.900
Okay, enough! I am a good dad!
All right?

18:28.983 --> 18:31.945
I love my kids and they love me.

18:32.028 --> 18:35.281
And you criticizing everything
I do around them, it just--

18:35.365 --> 18:38.410
you suck the joy
out of being a dad.

18:38.493 --> 18:40.620
What joy? You look miserable
half the time you're with them.

18:40.704 --> 18:43.873
I look miserable because
you are in the room.

18:45.959 --> 18:47.127
Well, there it is.

18:48.169 --> 18:49.796
You know what? Yeah, there--
actually, th-there it is.

18:49.879 --> 18:52.966
There it is. All this time
working with Dianne

18:53.049 --> 18:55.593
trying to figure out how
we ended up where we are now.

18:55.677 --> 18:57.804
It's-it's not because
I lost a bunch of weight,

18:57.887 --> 19:00.849
it's not because it took me
too long to-to bond with Jack

19:00.932 --> 19:03.935
or I moved to San Francisco
or any of the other BS

19:04.019 --> 19:06.312
that we talk about in there.
Turns out,

19:06.396 --> 19:08.440
the only crime
that I can consistently

19:08.523 --> 19:12.569
find myself guilty of
is not being Jack Pearson.

19:13.778 --> 19:16.281
-Okay, wow.
-No!

19:16.364 --> 19:18.116
Admit it. This marriage
has been a rigged game.

19:18.199 --> 19:20.118
-What?
-I am sorry that I like

19:20.201 --> 19:23.621
putting on a suit to go to work
and Jack Pearson hated it.

19:23.705 --> 19:26.082
I'm sorry I don't
father my children exactly

19:26.166 --> 19:27.709
the way Jack Pearson did.

19:27.792 --> 19:29.919
I'm sorry that Jack Pearson died

19:30.003 --> 19:32.255
and you ended up having
to marry me instead of him!

19:32.339 --> 19:34.382
-Stop it!
-JACK: Mom, Dad, I need help!

19:35.925 --> 19:38.386
-KATE (sighs): Jack?
-TOBY: Jack?

19:39.429 --> 19:41.389
Boba Fett fell in the toilet.

19:41.473 --> 19:44.309
You guys have to stop yelling
now and get him out.

19:47.062 --> 19:50.607
Okay. Yeah. We'll get him out.

19:50.690 --> 19:52.942
Come on.
I'll help you back to bed.

20:05.622 --> 20:10.919
I promised myself that I would
never be like my parents.

20:11.002 --> 20:13.213
That I wouldn't put my kids
through listening

20:13.296 --> 20:15.382
to crap like that.

20:24.683 --> 20:26.893
It's over, Toby.

20:32.315 --> 20:33.775
It's time.

20:40.490 --> 20:42.325
(TV sportscaster
speaking indistinctly)

20:42.409 --> 20:43.493
Hey.

20:43.576 --> 20:45.620
Hi.

20:45.704 --> 20:50.125
Uh, I, uh, took the liberty
of ordering.

20:50.208 --> 20:51.668
Hope you like Guinness.

20:51.751 --> 20:54.587
Not really. But thanks.

20:59.926 --> 21:01.845
How about those Rams?

21:03.304 --> 21:07.976
Yeah, uh... we don't have to
do the whole small talk thing.

21:08.059 --> 21:09.477
Oh, thank God.

21:09.561 --> 21:12.230
Because I had absolutely
no follow-ups to

21:12.313 --> 21:14.357
"how about those Rams."

21:14.441 --> 21:16.026
Yeah. Thanks for coming.

21:16.109 --> 21:20.405
Um, I'll just, I'll-I'll
cut to the-the chase here.

21:20.488 --> 21:25.910
Um, you and Kate
are getting serious.

21:25.994 --> 21:28.496
Which means that you're going to
be spending a lot more time

21:28.580 --> 21:29.998
with Jack and Hailey.

21:30.081 --> 21:32.542
So I thought we were long
overdue for a real conversation

21:32.625 --> 21:36.254
about what I expect from you,

21:36.338 --> 21:38.465
regarding the way you behave
around them.

21:38.548 --> 21:40.258
Yeah. No, I totally agree.

21:40.342 --> 21:43.053
I too think it's important.

21:43.136 --> 21:46.348
Especially as, um...

21:46.431 --> 21:50.477
I plan to propose to Kate soon.

21:50.560 --> 21:52.896
I'm sorry to spring that on you.
If you need a moment...

21:52.979 --> 21:57.734
It's fine. I, uh,
I kind of saw that coming.

21:57.817 --> 21:59.486
(clears throat)

22:00.820 --> 22:02.655
Look, most importantly,

22:02.739 --> 22:04.657
is that you don't yell
around the kids.

22:04.741 --> 22:07.327
You don't yell around them
and you don't yell at them.

22:07.410 --> 22:09.746
Yeah, don't worry.
British people don't yell.

22:09.829 --> 22:11.956
Even when we're furious, we just

22:12.040 --> 22:14.000
wrinkle our noses
disapprovingly.

22:18.505 --> 22:21.091
I'm sure this is all pretty
rich coming from me, huh?

22:21.174 --> 22:24.552
Based on what you've heard
about me. As a dad.

22:24.636 --> 22:27.722
I've heard nothing
but good things as of late.

22:27.806 --> 22:30.642
Yeah. Not good enough, I guess.

22:32.060 --> 22:34.270
How do you mean?

22:38.983 --> 22:43.113
I thought if we worked hard,

22:43.196 --> 22:44.989
if we fixed what was broken,

22:45.073 --> 22:46.658
that we would...

22:48.368 --> 22:50.370
...that we would find our way
back to each other.

22:50.453 --> 22:52.622
But instead we got divorced
and, uh,

22:52.706 --> 22:55.041
Kate found her way to you. So...

22:56.668 --> 22:59.170
I-I'm sorry. This is, this is
kind of getting off the rails.

22:59.254 --> 23:02.340
Listen, Toby...

23:02.424 --> 23:07.554
there's not much I can say to
make this moment more palatable.

23:07.637 --> 23:09.556
But I will say...

23:11.558 --> 23:13.643
I love your children.

23:14.686 --> 23:18.314
And I consider it
a great privilege to...

23:18.398 --> 23:21.443
to help raise them.

23:25.196 --> 23:26.990
Th-Thank you.

23:28.116 --> 23:31.036
(cheering and whooping)

23:32.954 --> 23:35.206
Was that a, uh, field goal then?

23:36.875 --> 23:39.169
Good God, man,
do you not even understand

23:39.252 --> 23:40.879
the objective of this game?

23:40.962 --> 23:43.381
I thought I did until just now.

23:43.465 --> 23:45.925
If you want to marry
Kate Pearson, you have to have

23:46.009 --> 23:48.553
at least a general understanding
of American football.

23:48.636 --> 23:50.972
It is a huge deal in her family.

23:51.056 --> 23:52.807
It was huge to her father.

23:56.853 --> 24:00.607
Um... look, okay,
American football

24:00.690 --> 24:02.901
is not that different
from soccer.

24:02.984 --> 24:06.363
Except instead of kicking
a ball into a goal,

24:06.446 --> 24:09.157
you're trying to carry a ball
into an end zone.

24:11.076 --> 24:13.036
It's over, Toby.

24:15.497 --> 24:16.873
It's time.

24:20.627 --> 24:22.629
♪ ♪

24:32.847 --> 24:35.266
This is the unit
that's available.

24:38.353 --> 24:40.355
(exhales)

24:40.438 --> 24:46.111
Yeah, well, beige
is my favorite color.

24:46.194 --> 24:48.029
We just want to do whatever's
best for the kids.

24:48.113 --> 24:49.280
I'm glad to hear that.

24:49.364 --> 24:52.784
Divorce is never pleasant,
but it doesn't have to be ugly.

24:52.867 --> 24:55.620
The mediation process
helps you work together

24:55.704 --> 24:57.330
to decide the best way
to co-parent

24:57.414 --> 24:59.332
and divide assets.

25:01.459 --> 25:02.794
<i>AUTOMATED VOICE:</i>
<i>Floor B.</i>

25:06.673 --> 25:08.717
(over speaker):
♪ <i>But above all this</i> ♪

25:08.800 --> 25:10.468
♪ <i>I wish you</i> ♪

25:10.552 --> 25:14.556
♪ <i>Love</i> ♪

25:16.891 --> 25:19.769
♪ <i>And I...</i> ♪

25:22.188 --> 25:26.109
♪ <i>Will always love you</i> ♪

25:26.192 --> 25:27.861
(stifled laugh)

25:27.944 --> 25:31.364
♪ <i>I will always love you</i> ♪

25:31.448 --> 25:34.534
(both laughing)

25:34.617 --> 25:35.744
(elevator dings)

25:35.827 --> 25:36.953
<i>AUTOMATED VOICE:</i>
<i>Ground floor.</i>

25:37.037 --> 25:39.748
(both laughing)

25:42.751 --> 25:44.294
(Toby sighs)

25:46.755 --> 25:48.381
(Toby clears throat)

25:49.966 --> 25:51.009
Uh...

25:51.092 --> 25:52.010
♪ <i>I will always</i> ♪

25:52.093 --> 25:53.053
Okay.

25:53.136 --> 25:55.680
♪ <i>Love you.</i> ♪

26:00.894 --> 26:02.395
-Oh, come on, you're lying.
-I'm not lying!

26:02.479 --> 26:04.147
I don't have a least
favorite student.

26:04.230 --> 26:06.399
I think they're all very sweet
in their own ways and...

26:06.483 --> 26:08.318
Ugh, you're no fun.

26:08.401 --> 26:11.404
Actually that is not true.
You are extremely fun.

26:11.488 --> 26:15.909
I am enjoying our first date
very much, Kate Pearson.

26:15.992 --> 26:17.577
Me, too.

26:17.660 --> 26:19.662
(guitar playing)

26:25.877 --> 26:27.462
(singing in Spanish)

26:27.545 --> 26:29.964
Oh, uh, that's okay.

26:30.048 --> 26:33.802
-Th-Thank you though.
-(singing continues)

26:33.885 --> 26:36.388
This-this kind of, like,
personal attention

26:36.471 --> 26:38.139
makes me very uncomfortable.

26:38.223 --> 26:40.392
Well, breathe. Breathe, Philip.

26:40.475 --> 26:43.895
We're gonna get through these
nice men playing music for us.

26:43.978 --> 26:45.313
(singing fades)

26:45.397 --> 26:47.399
♪ ♪

26:52.112 --> 26:53.780
(applause)

26:53.863 --> 26:55.323
Can you excuse me for a sec?

26:57.742 --> 26:59.744
♪ ♪

27:01.663 --> 27:04.207
(men singing in Spanish
in distance)

27:14.592 --> 27:16.594
Everything all right?

27:24.352 --> 27:26.312
Philip, listen to me.

27:27.397 --> 27:30.734
I was married to
a wonderful man.

27:30.817 --> 27:32.902
And we loved each other a lot.

27:32.986 --> 27:34.696
And it wasn't enough.

27:37.032 --> 27:41.745
(sighs) We were both so scared
of pushing each other away

27:41.828 --> 27:45.081
that we just swallowed our
feelings, time after time.

27:45.165 --> 27:47.208
And I can never be in a
relationship like that again.

27:47.292 --> 27:49.377
Understood.

27:51.504 --> 27:53.673
So I'm gonna ask you directly.

27:55.842 --> 27:57.719
What are you doing with me?

27:57.802 --> 28:01.556
You are a serial womanizer

28:01.639 --> 28:04.225
who dates a string
of toothpick-sized women.

28:04.309 --> 28:06.936
I'm a recently divorced,

28:07.020 --> 28:10.982
non-toothpick-sized
mother of two.

28:12.108 --> 28:13.818
My life is... (sighs)

28:13.902 --> 28:15.862
it's messy, it's complicated

28:15.945 --> 28:17.864
and it's hard.

28:17.947 --> 28:20.450
And you spend your life
avoiding those things.

28:23.036 --> 28:25.205
So I'm gonna ask you again.

28:26.873 --> 28:28.708
What are you doing?

28:31.419 --> 28:33.380
Wait, are you not skinny?
I hadn't noticed.

28:33.463 --> 28:35.423
Are you ser--
Okay, you know what?

28:35.507 --> 28:37.425
You're clearly not capable of
having a real conversation.

28:37.509 --> 28:41.137
No, it is extremely
presumptuous of you

28:41.221 --> 28:44.766
to assume that I've avoided
messiness and complication

28:44.849 --> 28:47.769
just because I don't go around
talking about my feelings

28:47.852 --> 28:51.314
all the time like you Americans
do, more specifically you do.

28:52.482 --> 28:55.151
As you know,
I was married once, too.

28:56.194 --> 29:00.532
And she was beautiful
in an imperfect way.

29:00.615 --> 29:04.744
Bit of a crooked nose.
But it worked for her.

29:04.828 --> 29:06.996
And she was blind.

29:08.748 --> 29:11.918
We were happy for
a really long time.

29:12.002 --> 29:14.713
But we had trouble conceiving.

29:14.796 --> 29:17.465
I thought it was just
a sign that we

29:17.549 --> 29:18.883
weren't meant to have children.

29:18.967 --> 29:22.095
But she was determined.

29:22.178 --> 29:25.348
You know, we did
three rounds of IVF.

29:25.432 --> 29:30.270
Yeah, it consumed our time,
drained our bank balance,

29:30.353 --> 29:34.607
just sucked all the lightness
and laughter out of our home.

29:36.818 --> 29:41.114
She said she wanted to try
a fourth time and...

29:41.197 --> 29:43.199
I refused.

29:44.242 --> 29:48.872
She said I was giving up
on our life together.

29:48.955 --> 29:50.790
And I said...

29:52.709 --> 29:56.921
I said I no longer recognized
our life together,

29:57.005 --> 30:00.216
so what was there to give up on?

30:00.300 --> 30:04.888
She of course then packed a bag
to go to her mother's.

30:04.971 --> 30:09.559
And, um...
I didn't even say goodbye

30:09.642 --> 30:12.062
when the cab came
to pick her up.

30:19.152 --> 30:21.821
She only made it five minutes
down the road

30:21.905 --> 30:25.158
before she was hit
by a drunk driver.

30:27.160 --> 30:30.997
Killed instantly.

30:32.040 --> 30:33.667
My God.

30:36.127 --> 30:40.632
So to, uh,
to answer your question...

30:40.715 --> 30:45.637
I am trying...

30:45.720 --> 30:48.723
to be happy again.

30:48.807 --> 30:53.061
And... you,
you make me happy.

30:53.144 --> 30:55.105
So...

30:55.188 --> 30:57.732
that is-is what I am doing.

31:00.610 --> 31:04.280
I hope that's a-- is that
a satisfactory answer?

31:05.407 --> 31:07.492
Yes, it is.
(clears throat)

31:07.575 --> 31:09.911
Okay, good.

31:09.994 --> 31:11.996
♪ ♪

31:16.292 --> 31:18.086
Did you guys get a chance
to discuss

31:18.169 --> 31:20.088
your post-divorce housing plan
since our last session?

31:20.171 --> 31:22.215
Yes.

31:22.298 --> 31:23.883
We agreed that

31:23.967 --> 31:25.260
<i>I would stay in the house</i>
<i>with the kids,</i>

31:25.343 --> 31:28.179
<i>and that Toby would get</i>
<i>a place nearby.</i>

31:30.056 --> 31:32.308
♪ ♪

31:32.392 --> 31:34.019
(grunts)

31:48.199 --> 31:50.326
Hi.

31:52.370 --> 31:54.622
(whispering): Something
extraordinary has happened.

31:54.706 --> 31:57.250
They're both asleep.

32:01.379 --> 32:03.340
Can you believe it?

32:07.052 --> 32:11.556
-(Toby shushing)
-(floor creaking)

32:11.639 --> 32:15.310
♪ ♪

32:18.938 --> 32:21.191
You're both here.

32:33.161 --> 32:35.747
So, how was the petting zoo?

32:35.830 --> 32:37.248
Tuckered them out.

32:37.332 --> 32:40.460
Yeah. Yeah.
It was, uh, it was good.

32:46.007 --> 32:47.467
You know, Kate,
there's still time.

32:47.550 --> 32:49.177
We don't have to go through
with this.

32:54.349 --> 32:57.435
(whispers):
Toby, don't do this.

32:57.519 --> 32:59.270
We're signing the papers
in two days.

32:59.354 --> 33:05.151
We are getting better together,
aren't we?

33:05.235 --> 33:08.113
I mean, I-I'm making progress
with the kids, right?

33:10.782 --> 33:14.869
Yeah. Definitely. I see it.

33:14.953 --> 33:16.329
I feel it. I know they feel it.

33:16.413 --> 33:18.331
I think, I think we should go--

33:18.415 --> 33:19.666
we should go back
and see Dianne.

33:19.749 --> 33:22.168
That was where--
I wasn't, I wasn't really

33:22.252 --> 33:25.088
receptive to it at first,
but-but I-I will be this time.

33:25.171 --> 33:27.632
Toby, I don't want to
see Dianne again.

33:27.716 --> 33:30.427
I don't.

33:30.510 --> 33:32.178
I haven't felt this good
in a long time.

33:32.262 --> 33:35.515
Like, I-I feel like I can
actually breathe. You know?

33:35.598 --> 33:37.350
And I think that you're doing
so great with the kids

33:37.434 --> 33:40.520
because you have your space to
figure out your thing with them.

33:40.603 --> 33:41.646
Away from me.

33:41.730 --> 33:43.398
You know, they're happier, too.

33:43.481 --> 33:45.108
When they're with you,
when they're with me.

33:45.191 --> 33:47.277
Their smiles are starting
to come back.

33:47.360 --> 33:48.820
They will be happier--

33:48.903 --> 33:53.074
they will be happier
if we are back together.

33:53.158 --> 33:55.952
Did you not hear what he said
w-when he woke up?

33:57.037 --> 33:58.788
Yes.

34:00.081 --> 34:01.958
(sighs)

34:04.044 --> 34:05.128
I know that in the long run...

34:05.211 --> 34:06.463
Kate, do not do this.

34:06.546 --> 34:09.341
Okay? Don't do this, please.

34:09.424 --> 34:12.635
I am terrified. I don't--
I don't want to be alone.

34:12.719 --> 34:14.554
Okay? I-I don't want to
have to start over.

34:14.637 --> 34:17.307
I don't want to have to live
half of my life without my kids.

34:17.390 --> 34:20.518
We can, we can, we can
get better. I know that we can.

34:20.602 --> 34:24.397
This cannot be the way
that our story ends.

34:27.108 --> 34:29.944
Please, please, please,
this-this-this cannot...

34:30.028 --> 34:32.906
this-this can't, this cannot be
the way that it ends. Okay?

